struct ExposeSyntaxContext {
    top_level_mark: Mark,
    unresolved_mark: Mark,
}
impl VisitMut for ExposeSyntaxContext {
    fn visit_mut_ident(&mut self, node: &mut Ident) {
        let new_name: Atom = format!(
            "{}_{}{}{}",
            node.sym,
            node.ctxt.as_u32(),
            if node.ctxt.has_mark(self.top_level_mark) {
                "_top"
            } else {
                ""
            },
            if node.ctxt.has_mark(self.unresolved_mark) {
                "_unres"
            } else {
                ""
            },
        )
        .into();
        node.sym = new_name;
    }
}

fn parse(
    code: String,
    filename: &str,
    cm: &Arc<SourceMap>,
) -> PResult<(Program, SingleThreadedComments)> {
    let source_file = cm.new_source_file(Arc::new(FileName::Real(filename.into())), code);
    let comments = SingleThreadedComments::default();

    let lexer = Lexer::new(
        Syntax::Typescript(TsSyntax {
            ..Default::default()
        }),
        // Syntax::Es(EsSyntax {
        //     jsx: true,
        //     ..Default::default()
        // }),
        Default::default(),
        StringInput::from(&*source_file),
        Some(&comments),
    );
    let mut parser = Parser::new_from(lexer);
    match parser.parse_program() {
        Err(err) => Err(err),
        Ok(program) => Ok((program, comments)),
    }
}

fn emit(program: &Program, comments: &SingleThreadedComments, cm: Arc<SourceMap>) -> String {
    let mut buf = vec![];
    {
        let writer = Box::new(JsWriter::new(cm.clone(), "\n", &mut buf, None));
        let config = codegen::Config::default().with_minify(false);
        let mut emitter = codegen::Emitter {
            cfg: config,
            comments: Some(&comments),
            cm,
            wr: writer,
        };
        emitter.emit_program(program).unwrap();
    }

    String::from_utf8(buf).unwrap()
}
```

utooland/utoo#2526.body:
### What problem does this feature solve?

Refer to webpack: https://webpack.js.org/configuration/output/#outputchunkloadingglobal

This configuration is mainly for adapting Turbopack's mounting capabilities in micro-frontends and iframe scenarios, which Turbopack currently lacks.

Current Turbopack runtime status:

```ts

(globalThis.TURBOPACK || (globalThis.TURBOPACK = []).push(
))

(() => {

if (!Array.isArray(globalThis.TURBOPACK)) {

return;

}

// ... runtime logic

const chunksToRegister = globalThis.TURBOPACK;

globalThis.TURBOPACK = { push: registerChunk };

})

```

This type of runtime code structure works fine for SPA/MPA applications.

However, in scenarios involving micro-frontends or iframe-mounted applications, this situation can lead to conflicts. For example, if the main application has already treated `globalThis.TURBOPACK` as a function.

When the child application loads, the `if (!Array.isArray(globalThis.TURBOPACK))` condition will cause it to exit immediately.

Therefore, we need to provide turbopack with capabilities similar to webpack's `output.chunkloadingglobal`.

The runtime format of the main application should be:

```ts

(globalThis['masterApp'] || (globalThis['masterApp'] = []).push(
// chunk ids

))

(() => {

if (!Array.isArray(globalThis['masterApp'])) {

return;

}
})

```

The child application will also have its own global variable name mounted:

```ts

(globalThis['slaveApp'] || (globalThis['slaveApp'] = []).push(
// chunk ids

))

(() => {

if (!Array.isArray(globalThis['slaveApp'])) {

return;

}
})

```

### What does the proposed API look like?

Turbopack provides configuration support, and utoopack behaves similarly to webpack. To maintain consistency, enabled by default:

```ts
output: {
   chunkLoadingGlobal: 'xxx'
}
```

Actual behavior is similar to webpack:

- If the user has set this configuration, it will use the variable name defined in the configuration.

- If the user hasn't set this configuration, it will use `entry[].name`.

- `entry[].name` is an optional value. If the user hasn't set it, it will use the name from the project's `package.json` (here, simply port the webpack code).

